events.description: Release of quarterly labor market data including unemployment and employment growth.
Upcoming meeting of the Reserve Bank of New Zealand to determine the official cash rate.

facts.fact_text: The New Zealand dollar fell to $0.603 on Wednesday.

evidences.evidence_text: The New Zealand dollar edged lower to $0.603 on Wednesday

facts.fact_text: New Zealand's unemployment rate rose to 5.4% in the fourth quarter.

evidences.evidence_text: The country’s unemployment rate ticked up to 5.4% in the fourth quarter, its highest level since 2015

facts.fact_text: Employment grew by 0.5% in the fourth quarter.

evidences.evidence_text: employment rose by 0.5% over the quarter, stronger than the estimated 0.3% growth

claims.claim_text: The Reserve Bank of New Zealand will likely maintain the official cash rate at 2.25% this month.
claims.author: Market consensus

evidences.evidence_text: reinforcing expectations that policymakers will keep the official cash rate unchanged at 2.25% at their upcoming meeting later this month

claims.claim_text: There is a 78% probability of a 25 bps rate hike in September.
claims.author: Markets

evidences.evidence_text: a 25 bps increase is currently priced in at around 78%

claims.claim_text: The first interest rate hike is expected by December by most economists.
claims.author: Economists

evidences.evidence_text: most economists anticipate the first rate hike by December

evidence.evidence_text: The New Zealand dollar edged lower to $0.603 on Wednesday... as a mixed jobs report left policy expectations for later this month largely unchanged.
Overall, the figures were broadly in line with the Reserve Bank of New Zealand’s projections, reinforcing expectations that policymakers will keep the official cash rate unchanged
employment rose by 0.5% over the quarter... signaling a stabilization in the labor market.
